Topic modelinh - LDA

Guided practice

In this guided practice we will learn how to train a LDA model in R using

We will train LDA using unigrams:

token_unigrams <- data %>%
  select(id, president, year, text) %>% 
  unnest_tokens(word, text)

token_unigrams

Notice that unnest_tokens took care of several preprocessing stages:

  • Other columns, such as the line number each word came from, are retained.
  • Punctuation has been stripped.
  • By default, unnest_tokens() converts the tokens to lowercase, which makes them easier to compare or combine with other datasets. (Yo can use the to_lower = FALSE argument to turn off this behavior).

We can now eliminate stop words:

stop_words_data <- stop_words
stop_words_data <- stop_words_data %>% 
  add_row(word = c('united', 'states', 'u. s.', 'u.s', 
                   'program', 'programs',
                   'government', 'congress', 
                   'applause', 'tonight', 'nation', 'nations', 'national',
                   'administration',
                   'country', 'americans',
                   'public', 'people', 'america', 'american', 'world'))

token_unigrams <- token_unigrams %>%
  anti_join(stop_words_data)

We generate the word count table

word_count <- token_unigrams %>%
  group_by(id, president, year, word) %>%
  summarise(n = n()) %>%
  ungroup()

word_count

Our data frame word_counts is in a tidy form, with one-term-per-document-per-row. We need to transform it to a DocumentTermMatrix, the format required by topicmodels package. We can cast a one-token-per-row table into a DocumentTermMatrix with tidytext’s cast_dtm().

dtm <- word_count %>% cast_dtm(id, word, n)
tictoc::tic()
lda <- LDA(dtm, k = 6, control = list(seed = 1234))
tictoc::toc()
18.414 sec elapsed
word2topics <- tidy(lda, matrix = "beta")
word2topics

The output of applying tidy() to LDA object is a table in one-topic-per-term-per-row format. For each combination, the model computes the probability of that term being generated from that topic. For example, the term “accurately” has an almost zero probability of being generated from topics 2 or 3, but it increases to 0.00013 to belong to topic 1.

Let’s find the most frequent terms for each topic and make a nice plot:

top_terms <- word2topics %>%
  group_by(topic) %>%
  slice_max(beta, n = 10) %>% 
  ungroup() %>%
  arrange(topic, -beta)

top_terms %>%
  mutate(term = reorder_within(term, beta, topic)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(beta, term, fill = factor(topic))) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~ topic, scales = "free") +
  scale_y_reordered()
